By the Law of Cosines on triangle $AQR$,
\[AR^2 = AQ^2 + QR^2 - 2 \cdot AQ \cdot QR \cdot \cos 60^\circ = x^2 + 25 - 5x.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABR$,
\[AR^2 = AB^2 + BR^2 - 2 \cdot AB \cdot BR \cdot \cos 60^\circ.\]Since $\triangle ABC$ is a right triangle, $AB = \sqrt{AC^2 + BC^2} = \sqrt{(x + 3)^2 + (x + 2)^2} = \sqrt{2x^2 + 10x + 13}$.  Also, $BR = BP + PR = 2 + 5 = 7$.  Hence,
\[AR^2 = 2x^2 + 10x + 13 + 49 - 7 \sqrt{2x^2 + 10x + 13} = 2x^2 + 10x + 62 - 7 \sqrt{2x^2 + 10x + 13}.\]Setting these two expressions for $AR^2$ equal to each other, we get
\[x^2 + 25 - 5x = 2x^2 + 10x + 62 - 7 \sqrt{2x^2 + 10x + 13}.\]Then $x^2 + 15x + 37 = 7 \sqrt{2x^2 + 10x + 13}$.  Squaring both sides, we get
\[x^4 + 30x^3 + 289x^2 + 1110x + 1369 = 98x^2 + 490x + 637.\]This simplifies to $x^4 + 30x^3 + 191x^2 + 620x + 732 = 0$.  We can factor this as $(x + 2)^2 (x^2 + 26x + 183) = 0$.  The quadratic factor has no real roots, so $x = \boxed{-2}$.  (We discard the negative solution since $AQ$ must be positive.)

